<section id="paragraph">
    <h1>&lt;p&gt;</h1>
    <p>Paragraphs (like this one!) are by default limited to 55 characters width (or whatever <code>@text-measure</code> is set to). They have an aggressive, but not too aggressive, line height of 1.62 (also a variable!). Like buttons and tables, paragraphs support all the semantic classes.</p>
    <p class="info">I'm informing you of something.</p>
    <pre>&lt;p class="info"&gt;I'm informing you of something.&lt;/p&gt;</pre>
    <br>
    <p class="failure">I've made a huge mistake.</p>
    <pre>&lt;p class="failure"&gt;I've made a huge mistake.&lt;/p&gt;</pre>
    <br>
    <p>Of course, without a class they just look like normal paragraphs.</p>
    <pre>&lt;p&gt;Of course, without a class they just look like normal paragraphs.&lt;/p&gt;</pre>
    <br>
</section>

<section id="span">
    <h1>&lt;span&gt;</h1>
    <p>Spans with semantic classes will <span class="success">appear bolder</span> and take the color of the semantic class. Careful, though... sometimes action, reaction or info can end up <span class="failure">looking like links</span>.</p>
    <pre>&lt;span class="success"&gt;appear bolder&lt;/span&gt;</pre>
    <pre>&lt;span class="failure"&gt;looking like links&lt;/span&gt;</pre>
</section>

<section id="aside">
    <h1>&lt;aside&gt;</h1>
    <p>Asides center everything inside them using flexbox. On mobile, they stack up their contents. Asides are an easy way to present multiple pieces of content side by side.</p>
    <aside>This is an aside.</aside>
    <pre>&lt;aside&gt;This is an aside.&lt;/aside&gt;</pre>
    <br>
    <p>It's useful for buttons:</p>
    <aside>
        <button>I'm centered!</button>
        <button class="failure">Me too</button>
    </aside>
    <pre>&lt;aside&gt;
    &lt;button&gt;I'm centered!&lt;/button&gt;
    &lt;button class="failure"&gt;Me too&lt;/button&gt;
&lt;/aside&gt;</pre>
    <br>
    <p>Asides support semantic classes, which makes them good for notification messages:</p>
    <aside class="failure">
        <p>You just deleted the <strong>entire site</strong>.</p>
        <button>Okay</button>
    </aside>
    <pre>&lt;aside class="failure"&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;You just deleted the &lt;strong&gt;entire site&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;button&gt;Okay&lt;/button&gt;
&lt;/aside&gt;</pre>
    <br>
    <aside class="success">
        <p>You've updated your profile.</p>
    </aside>
    <pre>&lt;aside class="success"&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;You've updated your profile.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/aside&gt;</pre>
    <br>
    <aside>
        <h6>Join our newsletter</h6>
        <form>
            <aside>
                <input type="text" name="firstname">
                <button onclick="return false" class="reaction">Submit</button>
            </aside>
        </form>
    </aside>
    <pre>&lt;aside&gt;
    &lt;h6&gt;Join our newsletter&lt;/h6&gt;
    &lt;form&gt;
        &lt;aside&gt;
            &lt;input type="text" name="firstname"&gt;
            &lt;button class="reaction"&gt;Submit&lt;/button&gt;
        &lt;/aside&gt;
    &lt;/form&gt;
&lt;/aside&gt;</pre>
    <br>
    <aside>
        <p>You're down to <span class="warning">596</span> credits.</p>
    </aside>
    <pre>&lt;aside&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;You're down to &lt;span class="warning"&gt;596&lt;/span&gt; credits.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/aside&gt;</pre>
    <br>
    <p>Nesting more than one aside inside another will <em>rapidly</em> accelerate the entropic heat death of the universe. Use a full grid solution to avoid prematurely warping the fabric of reality.</p>
</section>

<section id="button">
    <h1>&lt;button&gt;</h1>
    <p>Buttons are just <code>button</code> elements. There's no button class.</p>
    <p><button>Example button</button></p>
    <pre>&lt;button&gt;Example button&lt;/button&gt;</pre>
    <br>
    <p>Buttons can take a semantic class.</p>
    <p><button class="info">Example button</button></p>
    <pre>&lt;button class="info"&gt;Example button&lt;/button&gt;</pre>
    <br>
    <p>There are six semantic buttons by default, shown here:</p>
    <aside>
        <button type="button" class="action">Action</button>
        <button type="button" class="reaction">Reaction</button>
    </aside>
    <aside>
        <button type="button" class="success">Success</button>
        <button type="button" class="failure">Failure</button>
    </aside>
    <aside>
        <button type="button" class="info">Info</button>
        <button type="button" class="warning">Warning</button>
    </aside>
    <p>Semantic colors respond to the color scheme too, so <code>@success</code> will always be the <em>right</em> green (along with its corresponding button). They don't have any other classes to worry about, until you add them, but they do respond well to font size changes:</p>
    <aside>
        <button type="button" class="info" style="font-size:22px;">22 pixels big</button>
        <button type="button" class="failure" style="font-size:1.5em;">1.5em of failure</button>
    </aside>
    <aside>
        <button type="button" class="action" style="font-size:12px;">12px action button</button>
        <button type="button" class="warning" style="font-size:7px;">Warning, this is too small</button>
    </aside>
    <p>Buttons always have tinted (white) text. Sometimes they have darker background colors than the rest of the theme.</p>
    <aside class="success">
        <p>Buttons will inherit colors from color class parents, so you don't need redundant classes.</p>
        <button>Got it!</button>
    </aside>
    <pre>&lt;aside class="success"&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;Buttons will inherit colors from color class parents, so you
    don't need redundant classes.&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;button&gt;Got it!&lt;/button&gt;
&lt;/aside&gt;</pre>
</section>

